== Real Alchemy: A Primer of Practical Alchemy
_by Robert Allen Bartlett_

#hm-note[
  Bartlett's work is the modern standard for practical laboratory alchemy. It bridges the gap between ancient terminology and modern chemical understanding without losing the vitalistic essence. Bartlett studied at the Paracelsus Research Society under Frater Albertus (Albert Reidel) 1974–1983 and served as Chief Chemist at Paralab. He is a professional research and analytical chemist who has run state-of-the-art analyses on alchemical products. This book originated as a series of six-hour teaching classes.
]

=== Introduction: Practical Alchemy

#doctrine[
  Alchemy is an ancient Art and Science concerning the Mysteries of Life, of Consciousness and its Evolution. It has been described by the ancient masters as a sort of _"Celestial Agriculture."_ It lies at the root of every Western Esoteric tradition, including medicine and pharmacology. It has been called _"The Mother of all Science and Wisdom."_
]

- Alchemy is *not* a now-discredited method of turning lead into gold, nor merely a Jungian psychological metaphor — it is practical laboratory work.
- The goal: to assist Nature in her evolutionary process, separating the pure from the impure and reuniting them in greater perfection.
- Frater Albertus's definition: alchemy is about *Evolution* and "Raising the Vibratory Rate."
- The information derives from the *Hermetic Philosophy*, named after Hermes Trismegistus (Greek name for the Egyptian god Thoth — god of wisdom and inventor of all science and magic). Ancient sages called themselves the "Sons of Hermes" or "Sons of Wisdom."


=== Chapter One: A Brief History of Alchemy

- *Egypt (origin):* The priesthood of ancient Egypt developed skills in metallurgy, ceramics, medicine, mummification, and winemaking under an oath of secrecy. The operative forces of the universe were called the *Neteru* (from which we get "Nature"). Preparations combined physical processing with words, spells, and proper timing.
- The Greeks called Egypt *Khem* or *Khemet* ("The Black Land" — from the dark fertile Nile silt). Knowledge became *Khemia* ("The Black Art") in Greece.
- *Alexandria:* The Great Library (estimated ~1 million volumes) became the melting pot where Hermetic Philosophy and alchemy congealed as a Path to Spiritual Attainment.
- *290 C.E.:* Emperor Diocletian ordered destruction of all texts on gold-making fearing they could fund armies against Rome.
- *325 C.E.:* Rome officially became Christian; 391 C.E. the Emperor Theodosius made heresy punishable by death.
- *Arab world:* Alchemists fled east. The Arabic prefix *Al* was added to *Khemia* → *Al-Khemia* → *Alchemy*. Key figures: *Avicenna* (Ibn Sinna) and *Jabir* (Abu Musa Jabir ibn Hayaan) — his cryptic writing style gives us the word *Gibberish*.
- *Medieval Europe:* Alchemy became fashionable but was plagued by fraud. ~1310 Pope John XXII prohibited it; 1404 King Henry IV of England declared gold-making a crime.
- *Paracelsus* (born Theophrastus Bombast von Hohenheim, Switzerland, 1493): Revolutionized the Art; considered a father of modern chemistry and pharmaceutical medicine. Shifted alchemy from gold-making back to its original intent — medicines for body and soul. Believed murdered 1541.
- *Robert Boyle* and *Isaac Newton* studied alchemy in the 17th century. Newton considered himself more alchemist than physicist; his notes indicate he believed himself very close to success in metallic transmutation.
- ~1660: King Charles II signed the first Charter of the Royal Society; chemistry became an officially recognized science.
- 1800s: Alchemy disappeared into "Secret Societies." Early 1900s: H. Spencer Lewis founded *AMORC*. ~1940s: Albert Reidel (Frater Albertus) studied AMORC alchemy and later founded the *Paracelsus Research Society* (PRS) in 1960 (later accredited as Paracelsus College in the early 80s).
- Frater Albertus passed 1984. 1990s: *Philosophers of Nature (PON)* was formed to fill the void (closed late 1990s).


