==== Stages of the Great Work (Magnum Opus)

1. *Nigredo* (Black) — Putrefaction / Death of the matter.
2. *Peacock's Tail* — Iridescence; multiple colors appear at the surface.
3. *Albedo* (White) — Purification / Whitening.
4. *Citrinitas* (Yellow) — Transition phase (yellowness before red).
5. *Rubedo* (Red) — Perfection / Fixation = the Red Stone.

==== Safety Summary

#safety[
  - *Metallic mercury:* Extremely toxic and insidious. Never work with it without advanced laboratory skills, proper and verified ventilation, and full personal protective equipment.
  - *Niter mixtures (any fusion with niter):* Essentially gunpowder in a hot crucible. Add material SLOWLY. One cause of "Detonation" deaths among historical alchemists.
  - *Antimony (Stibnite):* Toxic metal similar to arsenic. The sulfide ore releases hydrogen sulfide gas during Kermes preparation — work outdoors, upwind, with respiratory protection.
  - *Lye / caustic alkalis (KOH, NaOH, K₂CO₃):* Severe burns to skin and especially eyes. Use splash goggles and chemical-resistant gloves always.
  - *Mineral acids and Aqua Regia:* Highly corrosive. Nitric acid produces toxic NOx fumes. Work in proper fume hood or outdoors.
  - *High temperatures (up to 1300°C):* Use Pyrex, porcelain crucibles, or iron retorts as appropriate. Avoid hot spots. Never use aluminum vessels.
  - *Mercury distillation retort:* Remove outlet tube from cooling water BEFORE the retort cools — risk of explosion from vacuum suck-back.
  - *Ammonium nitrate (Dew Salt):* Powerful oxidizer — can ignite fuel materials; specific mixture with Sal Ammoniac and zinc powder will self-ignite with a few drops of water.
  - Consume NO mineral preparations without deep understanding of the preparation and appropriate medical guidance.
  - *Know the theory thoroughly before attempting any praxis.*
]
